<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911217-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>911217-0023.</DOCID><HL>   `Reynolds Rap' Host   Sentenced to 17 Years   In Prison for Fraud</HL><DATE>12/17/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- R.G. Reynolds, a former radio andtelevision financial talk show host with a nationalfollowing, was sentenced to 17 years in prison by U.S.District Judge Manuel L. Real.   Mr. Reynolds, 44 years old, of Laguna Niguel, Calif., hadbeen found guilty by a jury on Nov. 7 of 13 counts of mailfraud and two counts of witness tampering. Judge Real alsoordered Mr. Reynolds, who hosted a nationally syndicatedfinancial radio talk show called &quot;The Reynolds Rap,&quot; to payrestitution totaling $420,955 to the 13 people named asvictims in the indictment.</LP><TEXT>   Assistant U.S. Attorney Ronni B. MacLaren said evidence atthe trial showed that Mr. Reynolds induced more than 70people, most of whom were inexperienced investors, to providehim large sums of money to invest in the stock and futuresmarkets between January 1985 and April 1987.   Mr. Reynolds then sent the victim investors false monthlyaccount statements showing enormous profits of as much as200% to 300%, Ms. MacLaren said. In fact, Mr. Reynolds wasspending the investors' money for his own personal use and topay the operating expenses of his companies, she said.Investors lost a total of $1.3 million.   In addition, evidence at the trial established that Mr.Reynolds tried to persuade a witness to destroy a documentthat had been subpoenaed by the grand jury investigating thecase, Ms. MacLaren said.   An attorney for Mr. Reynolds couldn't be reached forcomment.</TEXT></DOC>